34th stellation of the Icosahedron.  I made prototypes out of paper, but the model in the picture is cardboard, much stronger and more rigid.

I cut out the faces(a face is one triangle so in the pictures that show a blueprint there are 5 faces already connected; the longer spikes is made of isosceles triangles), taped them together, and then painted it.
You will need 12 of the larger "spikes" and 12 smaller "spikes". If you were to print out the pictures of triangles I've attached, they would form a model that measures about 14" across from point to point.
If you use cardboard you need to cut out individual faces because cardboard is thick enough that you can't fold the 5 triangles into a "spike". And I found that its easiest to tape them together if you make 12 larger spikes that each have 10 small faces taped to them. That way you can connect the small faces to each other and the larger spikes are already attached. That's hard to describe, but look at the photo of me making a model. You can see a stack of spikes that have the faces of other spikes already taped to them. And to the right of the stack is a single face with 2 of the smaller triangular faces taped to it. That picture basically shows the steps. On the right is step 1: a large face with 2 smaller faces attached. In the middle is step 2: 5 step "1"s taped together to make a spike. And then on the left step 3.

description.text: Thing to add.

If music is not enough for you, you could simply add a lightshow.
While trying to decorate and personalize my turntable I came up with this idea. Take a look at the video and see a stroboeffect, beatsync flashing lights and even colored sequences for your turntable. Take a look at the video to see how it works. http://youtu.be/zpftUBy3FbQ

Everything is written in OpenSCAD and documented. (In total more than 1000 lines of code)
Just download the code and modify. (Bring some time, rendering can take very long.) All parts are printable without support material in an area by 10x10cm. To construct your own lighteffectswheel, you have the choice between several components. groundplaneWithAxis: As the name says, this is necessary to print. chaserone: A wheel with one gap, which generates flashing lights.
chaserstrobo: A wheel with three gaps, which generates a strobo effect.
chasercolored: A wheel with no holes, but thin walls. This should be printed in white. Insert a paperstripe as you can see in the video to generate coloreffects. cap1: the cap to close the wheel. This one has extra holes for a connector.
cap2: the cap to close the wheel. This one has no holes for connectors, but a chamfer for the hole in the middle. Use this one if you have to much friction with cap1. connectros: may not necessary. Use the connectors, if your cap doesn´t stay in place. crossedwheels: use them to adjust the height and put one on top to stabelize the chaserwheel. They are 2/3/4/5/10 mm high. planetary_assembled: take a look at it ;)
planetary_printable: parts for the planetary wheel with the ghosts. Getting Started: 1) Build your own Stroboeffect:
print groundplaneWithAxis, chaserstrobo, cap1, crosses.
push the cap into chaserstrobo, so that the teeth are below.
Then follow the steps shown in the video.
Use the "crossed-wheels" to adjust the height. 2) Build your own Coloreffect:
print groundplaneWithAxis (if not already printed), chasercolored, cap1, crosses (if not already printed)
take a piece of paper and cut a paperstripe of ~250x25mm. use highlighters and paint your effect. put the stripe into the wheel. 3) Build a wheel with rotating ghosts:
print groundplaneWithAxis (if not already printed), chaser*, cap2 (may not necessary), crosses (if not already printed), planetary_printable (in high quality)
glue the planetary wheel on top of the chaser.

description.text: A laser cut layered acrylic enclosure for 8 NeoPixels on a strip, with bonus space for a BlinkStick Pro at the back! Turns the bare boards and wires into something a bit more rugged and desk friendly for the ultimate 8-pixel USB notification light! Check out http://blinkstick.com to get your own BlinkStick. This has been designed to let you slide a strip of Neopixels in and out without glue or permanent fixing. You can use it for any Neopixel project! See a video of it in action here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KM5WeHq5jw8

Materials
  • Acrylic
    • I used 3 different types, 3mm smoke for the rear, 6mm clear for the middle piece and 3mm frosted opal for the face and the stand.
    • The choice of the face material will affect the look of the LEDs, choose something to your taste.
    • I originally used 3mm for the middle piece and it didn't give enough room to easily slide the LED strip in and out. So use something thicker! I ended up with 6mm, but 4mm or 5mm would probably be OK depending on your wiring thickness.
  • Acrylic Solvent
    • I used "Plastic Weld"
  • 6 x M3x10mm Screws
  • 3 x M3x20mm Hex Spacers
  • Double sided tape to fix the BlinkStick.
    • Instructions Pixel Strip
  • Download the SVG and convert to your laser cutters format of choice
    • I use the Laser at London Hackspace which needs DXF, easily exported from Inkscape.
  • All black lines are cuts, try and make the smaller cuts first and don't cut the red text, its for info only!
  • Place the 3 long pieces together in the right order, tightly tape them together with 4 small pieces of Sellotape.
  • Using a syringe and needle, run a very small bead of Plastic Weld along the edges between the layers. Capillary effect will take the solvent into the whole touching surface so long as they are help together tightly.
  • After around 30 seconds, you can remove the tape and make sure the glue has taken. It should have wicked under the tape but if its not perfect, add some now.
  • Slide in your strip of NeoPixels, wiring end last though the square hold in the back.
    • Stand
  • Take one side and screw in the three spacers with the machine screws.
  • Slot in the bed that the BlinkStick will sit on.
  • Line up the second side with the slots and screw holes and fix with the remaining 3 screws.
  • Using some strong double sided foam tape, fix your BlinkStick with the USB port over hanging to give you room to put a USB extension lead in.
  • The two slots in the back of the Pixel Strip will line up with the verticals of the stand. The angle is just right to slot it on without glue or screws and it will stay.
    • Now start making those LED blink!

My new YouTube Channel: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCnnw56J_TeOsF4M_F5pPPJQ In the quest for 3D printed liquid containers, the okay just got okay-er! While working on a different project, I needed to make a part that fit to a disposable flask's threaded opening. So I designed the neck of the opening and printed it to check the compatibility with the existing cap. It worked great so I was able to design that project and move along. But I was left with a threaded tube with nothing to do! The PhLAsk is just a simple hip flash with a threaded cap. I printed it in black PLA at 220 micron layer height, three shells and 20% in-fill. I filled it with water and left it in a dish overnight and it looks like there is no seeping. The cap doesn't seal 100% but it does so well enough to keep water from dripping out with gravity. A little pressure will cause a seep though. A gasket will fix this. VIDEO: http://youtu.be/PK_BjZQtTRw I have not tested other liquids with different surface tensions but for casual liquid portability, I will be using this little guy! Bottom's up! If you like what I do and want to help me do more, please consider supporting me on my Patreon page! http://www.patreon.com/ErikJDurwoodII Thanks!
